<p id="mwAwQ">The first of Maxwell's equations implies that the electric field is orthogonal to the direction the wave propagates.</p>

<dl id="mwAwU"><dd id="mwAwY"><span class="mwe-math-element" typeof="mw:Extension/math" about="#mwt603" data-mw='{"name":"math","attrs":{},"body":{"extsrc":"\\nabla \\times \\mathbf{E} = \\hat{\\mathbf{k}} \\times \\mathbf{E}_0 f&apos;\\left( \\hat{\\mathbf{k}} \\cdot \\mathbf{x} - c_0 t \\right) = -\\frac{\\partial \\mathbf{B}}{\\partial t}"}}' id="mwAwc"><span class="mwe-math-mathml-inline mwe-math-mathml-a11y" style="display: none;"><math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML" alttext="{\displaystyle \nabla \times \mathbf {E} ={\hat {\mathbf {k} }}\times \mathbf {E} _{0}f'\left({\hat {\mathbf {k} }}\cdot \mathbf {x} -c_{0}t\right)=-{\frac {\partial \mathbf {B} }{\partial t}}}">
