ve must have the following properties: 1) The field pattern travels with speed c (speed of light); 2) At every point within the wave... the electric field strength E equals "c" times the magnetic field strength B; 3) The electric field and the magnetic field are perpendicular to one another and to the direction of travel, or propagation."</li></ul></span></li><li about="#cite_note-2" id="cite_note-2"><a href="./Electromagnetic_radiation#cite_ref-2" rel="mw:referencedBy"><span class="mw-linkback-text">↑ </span></a> <span id="mw-reference-text-cite_note-2" class="mw-reference-text"><ul id="mwAyY"><li id="mwAyc"><cite class="citation book" about="#mwt6" typeof="mw:Transclusion" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"cite book ","href":"./Template:Cite_book"},"params":{"author":{"wt":"Browne, Michael"},"title":{"wt":"Physics for Engineering and Science, p427"},"edition":{"wt":"2nd"},"publisher":{"wt":"McGraw Hill/Schaum, New York."},"year":{"wt":"2013"},"isbn":{"wt":"978-0-07-161399-6"}},"i":0}}]}' id="mwAyg">Browne, Michael (2013). <i id="mwAyk">Physics for Engineering and Science, p427</i> (2nd ed.). McGraw Hill/Schaum, New York. <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./International_Standard_Book_Number" title="International Standard Book Number" id="mwAyo">ISBN</a><span typeof="mw:Entity" id="mwAys"> </span><a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Special:BookSources/978-0-07-161399-6" title="Special:BookSources/978-0-07-161399-6" id="mwAyw">978-0-07-161399-6</a>.</cite><span title="ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Abook&amp;rft.genre=book&amp;rft.btitle=Physics+for+Engineering+and+Science%2C+p427&amp;rft.edition=2nd&amp;rft.pub=McGraw+Hill%2FSchaum%2C+New+York.&amp;rft.date=2013&amp;rft.isbn=978-0-07-161399-6&amp;rft.au=Browne%2C+Michael&amp;rfr_id=info%3Asid%2Fen.wikipedia.org%3AElectromagnetic+radiation" class="Z3988" about="#mwt6" id="mwAy0"></span><link rel="mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href="mw-data:TemplateStyles:r879151008" about="#mwt6" typeof="mw:Extension/templatestyles" data-mw='{"name":"templatestyles","attrs":{"src":"Module:Citation/CS1/styles.css"},"body":{"extsrc":""}}' id="mwAy4"/>; p319: "For historical reasons, different portions of the EM spectrum are given different names, although they are all the same kind of thing. Visible light constitutes a narrow range of the spectrum, from wavelengths of about 400-800 nm.... ;p 320 "An electromagnetic wave carries forward momentum... If the radiation is absorbed by a surface, the momentum drops to zero and a force is exerted on the surface... Thus the radiation pressure of an electromagnetic wave is (formula)."</li></ul></span></li><li about="#cite_note-3" id="cite_note-3"><a href="./Electromagnetic_radiation#cite_ref-3" rel="mw:referencedBy"><span class="mw-linkback-text">↑ </span></a> <span id="mw-reference-text-cite_note-3" class="mw-reference-text"><cite class="citation journal" about="#mwt8" typeof="mw:Transclusion" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"cite journal","href":"./Template:Cite_journal"},"params":{"last1":{"wt":"Maxwell"},"first1":{"wt":"J. Clerk"},"title":{"wt":"A Dynamical Theory of the Electromagnetic Field"},"journal":{"wt":"Philosophical Transactions of the Royal Society of London"},"volume":{"wt":"155"},"pages":{"wt":"459–512"},"doi":{"wt":"10.1098/rstl.1865.0008"},"date":{"wt":"1 January 1865"}},"i":0}}]}' id="mwAy8">Maxwell, J. Clerk (1 January 1865). "A Dynamical Theory of the Electromagnetic Field". <i id="mwAzA">Philosophical Transactions of the Royal Society of London</i>. <b id="mwAzE">155</b>: 459–512. <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Digital_object_identifier" title="Digital object identifier" id="mwAzI">doi</a>:<a rel="mw:ExtLink" class="external text" href="//doi.org/10.1098%2Frstl.1865.0008" id="mwAzM">10.1098/rstl.1865.0008</a>.</cite><span title="ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Ajournal&amp;rft.genre=article&amp;rft.jtitle=Philosophical+Transactions+of+the+Royal+Society+